senses.definition: The act of going.
A turn at something, or in something (e.g. a game).
usageExamples: It’s your go.
You’ve been on that pinball machine long enough—now let your brother have a go.

senses.definition: An attempt, a try.
usageExamples: I’ll give it a go.

senses.definition: An approval or permission to do something, or that which has been approved.
usageExamples: We will begin as soon as the boss says it's a go.

senses.definition: An act; the working or operation.
A circumstance or occurrence; an incident, often unexpected.
The fashion or mode.
usageExamples: quite the go

senses.definition: Noisy merriment.
usageExamples: a high go

senses.definition: A glass of spirits; a quantity of spirits.
Power of going or doing; energy; vitality; perseverance.
usageExamples: There is no go in him.

senses.definition: The situation where a player cannot play a card which will not carry the aggregate count above thirty-one.
A period of activity.
usageExamples: ate it all in one go

senses.definition: (British slang) A dandy; a fashionable person.
To move:

subSenses.definition: To move through space (especially to or through a place). (May be used of tangible things like people or cars, or intangible things like moods or information.)
usageExamples: Chris, where are you going?
There's no public transit where I'm going.
This train goes through Cincinnati on its way to Chicago.
Why don’t you go with us?
Wow, look at him go!

subSenses.definition: To move or travel through time (either literally—in a fictional or hypothetical situation in which time travel is possible—or in one's mind or knowledge of the historical record). (See also go back.)
usageExamples: Fans want to see the Twelfth Doctor go to the 51st century to visit River in the library.
Yesterday was the second-wettest day on record; you have to go all the way back to 1896 to find a day when more rain fell.

subSenses.definition: To navigate (to a file or folder on a computer, a site on the internet, a memory, etc).
To move (a particular distance, or in a particular fashion).
usageExamples: This car can go circles around that one.
We've only gone twenty miles today.

subSenses.definition: To move or travel in order to do something, or to do something while moving.
usageExamples: Let's go shopping.
We went swimming.

subSenses.definition: To leave; to move away.
usageExamples: I really must be going.
Please don't go!
Workmen were coming and going at all hours of the night.

subSenses.definition: To walk; to travel on one's feet.

senses.definition: (chiefly of a machine) To work or function (properly); to move or perform (as required).
usageExamples: The engine just won't go anymore.

senses.definition: To start; to begin (an action or process).
usageExamples: Get ready, get set, go!
Here goes nothing.
Let's go and hunt.
On your marks, get set, go!
On your marks, set, go!

senses.definition: To take a turn, especially in a game.
usageExamples: It’s your turn; go.

senses.definition: To attend.
usageExamples: I go to school at the schoolhouse.
She went to Yale.
They only go to church on Christmas.

senses.definition: To proceed:

subSenses.definition: To proceed (often in a specified manner, indicating the perceived quality of an event or state).
usageExamples: "How are things going?" "Not bad, thanks."
That went well.

subSenses.definition: (with another verb, sometimes linked by and) To proceed (especially to do something foolish).
usageExamples: He just went and punched the guy.
Why'd you have to go and do that?
Why'd you have to go do that?

senses.definition: To follow or travel along (a path):

subSenses.definition: To follow or proceed according to (a course or path).
usageExamples: Let's go this way for a while.
She was going that way anyway, so she offered to show him where it was.

subSenses.definition: To travel or pass along.

senses.definition: To extend (from one point in time or space to another).
usageExamples: This property goes all the way to the state line.

senses.definition: To lead (to a place); to give access to.
usageExamples: Does this road go to Fort Smith?

senses.definition: To become. (The adjective that follows usually describes a negative state.)
usageExamples: After failing as a criminal, he decided to go straight.
I went crazy / went mad.
You'll go blind.  The milk went bad.

senses.definition: To assume the obligation or function of; to be, to serve as.
To continuously or habitually be in a state.
usageExamples: I don't want my children to go hungry.
We went barefoot in the summer.

senses.definition: To come to (a certain condition or state).
usageExamples: They went into debt, she goes to sleep around 10 o'clock.
the local shop wants to go digital, and eventually go global.

senses.definition: To change (from one value to another) in the meaning of wend.
usageExamples: The traffic light went straight from green to red.

senses.definition: To turn out, to result; to come to (a certain result).
usageExamples: How did your meeting with Smith go?

senses.definition: To tend (toward a result).
usageExamples: These experiences go to make us stronger.
Well, that goes to show you.

senses.definition: To contribute to a (specified) end product or result.
usageExamples: qualities that go to make a lady / lip-reader / sharpshooter

senses.definition: To pass, to be used up:

subSenses.definition: (of time) To elapse, to pass; to slip away. (Compare go by.)
usageExamples: The time went slowly.

subSenses.definition: To end or disappear. (Compare go away.)
usageExamples: After three days, my headache finally went.

subSenses.definition: To be spent or used up.
usageExamples: His money went on drink.

senses.definition: To die.
To be discarded.
usageExamples: This chair has got to go.

senses.definition: To be lost or out:

subSenses.definition: (of a wicket) To be lost.
(of a batsman) To be out.

senses.definition: To break down or apart:

subSenses.definition: To collapse or give way, to break apart.
To break down or decay.
usageExamples: My mind is going.
She's 83; her eyesight is starting to go.
This meat is starting to go off.

senses.definition: To be sold.
usageExamples: Everything must go.
The car went for five thousand dollars.

senses.definition: To be given, especially to be assigned or allotted.
usageExamples: The award went to Steven Spielberg.
The property shall go to my wife.

senses.definition: To survive or get by; to last or persist for a stated length of time.
usageExamples: Can you two go twenty minutes without arguing?!
How long can you go without water?
I've gone ten days now without a cigarette.
We've gone without your help for a while now.

senses.definition: To have a certain record.
usageExamples: The team is going five in a row.
They've gone one for three in this series.

senses.definition: To be authoritative, accepted, or valid:

subSenses.definition: To have (final) authority; to be authoritative.
usageExamples: Whatever the boss says goes, do you understand?

subSenses.definition: To be accepted.
usageExamples: Anything goes around here.

subSenses.definition: To be valid.

senses.definition: To say (something), to make a sound:

subSenses.definition: To say (something, aloud or to oneself). (Often used in present tense.)
usageExamples: As soon as I did it, I went "that was stupid."
I go, "As if!" And she was all like, "Whatever!"

subSenses.definition: To make the (specified) sound.
usageExamples: Cats go "meow". Motorcycles go "vroom".

subSenses.definition: To sound; to make a noise.
usageExamples: I woke up just before the clock went.

senses.definition: To be expressed or composed (a certain way).
usageExamples: As the story goes, he got the idea for the song while sitting in traffic.
The tune goes like this.

senses.definition: To resort (to).
usageExamples: I'll go to court if I have to.

senses.definition: To apply or subject oneself to:

subSenses.definition: To apply oneself; to undertake; to have as one's goal or intention. (Compare be going to.)
usageExamples: He went to pick it up, but it rolled out of reach.
He's going to leave town tomorrow.
I wish you'd go and get a job.
I'm going to join a sports team.

subSenses.definition: To make an effort, to subject oneself (to something).
usageExamples: I never thought he'd go so far as to call you.
She went to great expense to help them win.
You didn't have to go to such trouble.

subSenses.definition: To work (through or over), especially mentally.
usageExamples: I've gone over this a hundred times.
Let's not go into that right now.

senses.definition: To fit (in a place, or together with something):

subSenses.definition: (often followed by a preposition) To fit.
usageExamples: Do you think the sofa will go through the door?
The belt just barely went around his waist.

subSenses.definition: To be compatible, especially of colors or food and drink.
usageExamples: This shade of red doesn't go with the drapes.
White wine goes better with fish than red wine.

subSenses.definition: To belong (somewhere).
usageExamples: My shirts go on this side of the wardrobe.
This piece of the jigsaw goes on the other side.

senses.definition: To date.
usageExamples: He's been going with her for two weeks.
How long having they been going together?

senses.definition: To attack:

subSenses.definition: To fight or attack.
usageExamples: I went at him with a knife.

subSenses.definition: To attack.

senses.definition: To be in general; to be usually.
usageExamples: As sentences go, this one is pretty boring.

senses.definition: To take (a particular part or share); to participate in to the extent of.
usageExamples: Let's go halves on this.

senses.definition: To yield or weigh.
usageExamples: Those babies go five tons apiece.

senses.definition: To offer, bid or bet an amount; to pay.
usageExamples: I'll go a ten-spot.
I'll go you a shilling.
That's as high as I can go.
We could go two fifty.

senses.definition: To enjoy. (Compare go for.)
usageExamples: I could go a beer right about now.

senses.definition: To urinate or defecate.
usageExamples: Have you managed to go today, Mrs. Miggins?
I really need to go.

senses.definition: Working correctly and ready to commence operation; approved and able to be put into action.
A strategic board game, originally from China, in which two players (black and white) attempt to control the largest area of the board with their counters.
